voice_to_text: Sostenía el documento por encima de su cabeza sin pensar. Cuando la luz pasó a través de la página. De repente, vio palabras ocultas bajo el marcador negro. Era información clasificada, información que no se suponía que debía ver. Pero los números en los que su equipo trabajado durante días no coincidían con los del informe. Y esa discrepancia era la razón por la que el lanzamiento del cohete rextone había fracasado. Determinada, subió la escalera y, utilizando los datos del archivo, comenzó a recalcular la trayectoria del cohete desde cero. Las fórmulas eran complejas, pero estaba cerca de resolverlas. En ese momento, sintió la necesidad de ir al baño, pero todos los baños en el edificio eran solo para el personal blanco. Tuvo que caminar uno coma ocho, cero cero metros, más de una milla para llegar al único que estaba destinado para los empleados negros. Mientras ella estaba fuera, sus cálculos llamaron la atención de sus compañeros. No podían creer lo que estaban viendo. La trayectoria correcta estaba ahí, ¿en la pizarra de quién es este trabajo? Catherine goebel, señor. Catherine regresó rápidamente a la oficina, solo para ser recibida con desconfianza. El director ya estaba esperando. Pensaba que podría ser una espía. Después de todo, toda la información esencial había sido tachada. No había forma que ella pudiera haber resuelto las ecuaciones bajo presión. Catherine explicó que simplemente había usado la luz para ver lo que estaba oculto debajo. El director levantó el documento y Efectivamente, la luz reveló las palabras ocultas. Su actitud cambió de inmediato. Ordenó al personal que dejara de tachar los documentos y por primera vez, catherine recibió acceso a los materiales clasificados que necesitaba. Pero cuando el director entró a su oficina, ansioso por trabajar con ella, la encontró con su asiento vacío. Catherine estaba afuera, bajo la lluvia torrencial, dirigiéndose hacia el baño para personas de color. Empapada hasta los huesos, trató de secarse con toallas de papel, pero ni siquiera había papel higiénico en ese baño. Regresó a la oficina empapada y antes de que pudiera explicar, el director exigió, dónde has estado durante los últimos cuarenta minutos en el baño. Señor, el baño. No te creo. Había un baño justo al final del pasillo. ¿Por qué te tardaste cuarenta minutos? Entonces catherine le dijo, la verdad, no me dejan usar ese baño. Tengo que caminar por todo el campus. No puedo usar las bicicletas de la oficina. No puedo tocar la cafetera común. Ni siquiera me dejan usar faldas o tacones. Todo por el color de mi piel y trabajo como una mula día y noche viviendo de café de una cafetera que nadie quiere tocar. La sala cayó completamente en silencio. El director no dijo nada. Catherine, exhausta y al límite, empacó sus cosas y se marchó. Esta mujer que se atrevió a hablar, terminaría haciendo contribuciones revolucionarias para toda la industria aeroespacial. Catherine había mostrado signos de genialidad desde que era niña, mientras otros niños Aprendían aritmética básica. Ella ya resolvía problemas de geometría analítica. Su profesora, asombrada por su talento, instó a sus padres a enviarla a las mejores escuelas. No los defraudó. A los dieciocho años había terminado la universidad. Sus extraordinarias habilidades matemáticas le consiguieron un empleo en la nasa. Pensó que sería el comienzo de algo grandioso, pero la realidad la golpeó fuerte. La mayoría de sus compañeros no creían en ella. Le daban miradas frías, la desestimaban con condescendencia. Le asignaban trabajo sin explicaciones. Pero entre ellos había un director que vio su valor. No le importaba el color de su piel, él veía su brillantez. Le asignó no solo tareas regulares, sino que también le pidió que verificara los cálculos de otros ingenieros. Eso no le gustó nada. A hilton, el líder del equipo, no podía soportar que alguien desafiara su autoridad en matemáticas. Entonces tachó partes clave de los documentos con un marcador y luego le dejó una montaña de archivos en su escritorio. Aun así, katherine aceptó el desafío, pero cada vez que necesitaba ir al baño perdía un tiempo precioso. A pesar de todo, nunca dejó que su trabajo se retrasara. El estrés era implacable. El café se convirtió en su único consuelo, pero cuando intentaba usar la cafetera común, sentía que todos la observaban. Al día siguiente, un pequeño bote de café apareció en su escritorio, marcado con su nombre. Lo levantó en silencio. Estaba completamente vacío. No se quejó, creía que su talento hablaría Por sí mismo, antes de que pudiera terminar el primer montón de archivos, otro montón aterrizó en su escritorio. No fue hasta caída la noche que finalmente alcanzó a ponerse al día. Pero cuando entregó su trabajo al director, lo tiró a la basura sin siquiera mirarlo. No fue un insulto. Los datos ya estaban desactualizados. El director no solo exigía números, quería visión, previsión. Necesitaba respuestas antes de que los problemas surgieran. Sin eso, nunca despegarían. Para avanzar, emitió una orden dura, quedarse trabajando horas extras sin fin o empacar y marcharse. Todos eligieron quedarse. No tenían otra opción. Se concentraron, se esforzaron al límite y luego el director notó que catherine ya no estaba. Esperó cuarenta minutos antes de que ella regresara. Cuando le preguntó dónde había estado, catherine soltó todo, todo lo que había soportado, todo el trato injusto, todo el sufrimiento silencioso. Y aquí volvemos al momento en el que comenzamos. Catherine pensó que todo había terminado, que la despedirían. Pero en lugar de eso, el director arrancó la etiqueta de su bote de café, caminó hacia el baño y arrancó el letrero que decía coloreado. Y luego hizo un anuncio sorprendente, uno que no solo cambiaría la vida de catherine, sino que ayudaría a moldear el futuro de la exploración espacial humana. ¿Quieres saber qué pasó después? Sígueme para conocer el final de la historia

voice_to_text: My dad cheated on my mom with her friend, and now they have three kids. At their anniversary dinner, he announced a family vacation. I refused, saying, I hate your wife. I'm 17. When I was 9, my dad left my mom for her best friend. Yeah, you heard that right. Her best friend. The woman who used to come over for wine nights and complained about her own marriage. Turns out she wasn't just complaining. They got married six months after the divorce and had three kids together in rapid succession. My dad fought for weekend custody, and honestly, at first, I thought maybe he actually wanted to spend time with me. I was wrong. Every weekend was the same. He'd pick me up Friday night, and by Saturday morning, I was just another kid in his new family. Breakfast with all of us, family movie nights, Sunday park trips with the whole crew. He never wanted time with just me. It was always about making me fit into his new perfect family. The worst part? He kept pushing me to call his wife mom. He'd correct me in front of everyone. That's your mom, too, now? No, she's not. She's the woman who destroyed my actual mom. He even went for full custody three times. Three times. Each time claiming my mom was unfit because she was bitter and turning me against him. The judge never agreed. But here's what I never told anyone. Not even my mom. His wife was awful to me. When he wasn't looking, she'd smile and play the perfect stepmom role when he was around. But the second he left the room, her whole face would change. One time when I was 12, she cornered me in the hallway and said, you're the only thing standing between your father and true happiness, right? If you really loved him, you'd just stay with your mom full time. I was 12. 12 years old. This grown woman was telling me I was ruining her life. After that, I started finding excuses not to go. Homework, friends, birthday parties, anything. When I turned 14, I finally told my dad I didn't want to come anymore. He tried to fight it, even attempted to get full custody again when my mom started dating my stepdad. But I told the court I didn't want to go. They listened. For three years, I barely saw him. He text, sometimes call on my birthday. But mostly, I think he was relieved his perfect little family didn't need the bitter reminder of his first marriage anymore. More than five days ago, my phone rang. It was my dad. He said it was important that I come to dinner. When I said no, he called my mom and threatened to take her back to court for parental alienation if she didn't make me go. So I went. It was at this fancy Italian restaurant. Both sets of grandparents were there. His three kids were dressed up like it was a holiday card photo shoot.

voice_to_text: When did people realise I wasn't just arm candy? So I'm dating Mitchell. He's 56, I'm 28. And, yes, he's rich. Like, really rich. We met at the Starbucks, where I was working on my laptop. He loved that I wasn't trying to get his attention and that I added to my coffee, in his words, more sugar than the Boston Harbour needed in 1773. But here's what six months of dating him actually looks like. Waiters hand him the wine list, never me. His friends, wives talk to me like I'm five, explaining what investment means really slowly. The valet gives Mitchell my car keys every single time. At his country club, someone always asks what I'm studying. I graduated four years ago. Last week, his lawyer asked if I needed help reading the dinner menu. It had seven items on it. Mitchell's company Christmas party is everything I expected and worse. I'm wearing this gorgeous Chanel dress that I bought myself because I liked it. And not even five minutes in, one of the wives pulls me into the bathroom, puts her hand on my shoulder like she's about to deliver terrible news, and tells me I need to save the money Mitchell gives me for when this ends. When I mention having my own money, she laughs like I've told a joke and presses her friend's financial advisor card into my hand. He specializes in girls like me, apparently. Mitchell gets pulled into a work emergency, leaving Me at the bar where his call kids don't bother lowering their voices. How much do you think Mitchell spends on her monthly? One says, worth every penny at that age. Another answers, cheaper than my boat maintenance. When I approach and mention my startup work, they find it hilarious. One actually asks if Mitchell taught me the word portfolio. Another suggests I'm confusing shopping with investing. Then the boss himself walks over with his champagne and says the most insulting thing yet. When you and Mitchell are done, you should date my son. He's more age appropriate and needs a pretty girl. I say, I don't need anyone to take care of me, but he just pats my head like I'm a golden retriever. We all know what you need, sweetheart. I'm about to tell him exactly what I needed in that moment when I hear Mitchell's voice from the conference room. The door is cracked open, and he's on speaker phone, negotiating to buy a tech company. The seller is refusing his 10 million offer, insisting it's worth more, but won't explain why. Mitchell sounds increasingly desperate, repeatedly asking what he's missing. That's when my blood runs cold. I know this company. I know it intimately. I know exactly what Mitchell is missing. I push into the conference room. Before I can stop myself, Mitchell looks up, irritated at the interruption. He tells the seller on the phone, sorry, my girlfriend just wandered in. I'm already scanning the papers. Spread across the table, confirming what I suspected. The seller's voice crackles through the speaker, asking what's going on. I state simply that the company has three major clients not listed in the disclosure. Mitchell freezes. The seller's voice turns sharp, demanding to know how I could possibly know that. Mitchell starts apologizing for my intrusion, while the CEO appears in the doorway. Mitchell, that's confidential information. You shouldn't be sharing these things. His wife laughs, suggesting I overheard something, and I'm trying to sound smart, but I continue.

voice_to_text: My brother crashed his car and barely survived. My mom looked at the wreck and said, well, maybe this will finally teach him to be useful. Tyler was in the I C. U. With a fractured spine and internal bleeding. The crash happened on Highway 9 around midnight. A drunk driver ran a red light and t boned him at full speed. Tyler's car flipped three times before landing in a ditch. The paramedics said if the airbag hadn't deployed, he'd be dead. If he'd been going five miles faster, dead. If the car had flipped one more time, dead. I got the call at 2 a. M. From the hospital. Didn't hesitate. I threw on clothes and drove straight there. When I arrived, Tyler was already in surgery. The nurse said they were stabilizing his spine and checking for brain damage. I called my parents from the waiting room. My dad answered on the first ring. I could hear the panic in his voice as I explained what happened. He said he'd be there in 20 minutes. My mom, she answered after six rings. Her voice was annoyed. Do you know what time it is? Tyler's in the hospital. Car accident. It's bad. There was a pause and she said, well, is he going to live? We don't know yet. He's in surgery. Call me when you know something concrete. I have Pilates at 7. She hung up. My dad arrived 15 minutes later, still in his pajamas. He Thrown a coat over them and driven barefoot. His hands were shaking as we waited for news. Three hours passed before the surgeon came out. Tyler was stable, fractured spine, internal bleeding, broken ribs, collapsed lung, but he'd live. He'd need months of physical therapy, but he'd walk again. My dad broke down crying right there in the hallway. My mom showed up at noon, still in her tennis outfit from her morning match, white skirt, matching visor, got a hair out of place. She had a Starbucks cup in her hand. She walked into Tyler's room like she was visiting a distant relative. He was still sedated, hooked up to machines, barely recognizable under all the tubes and bandages. She stood at the foot of his bed for maybe 30 seconds. Then she looked at me and said, is he awake? Not yet. I said, they have him sedate.

voice_to_text: My rich uncle said he'd pay for college for whoever earned it through character, so I made sure he saw exactly what kind of character I had. While my cousins performed like circus animals. Uncle Morty was a multi millionaire, but treated family gatherings like auditions. Every holiday, my cousins would bring carefully selected gifts, research his interests, and compete for most worthy. I'm paying for college for one of you, he'd announce, but only for whoever shows real character, not entitlement. Madison took unpaid internships at companies he invested in. Simon switched from art to finance because Morty mentioned he respected practical majors. They'd memorize his opinions and perform them back like trained parrots. Meanwhile, I worked at a hardware store and spent Saturdays rebuilding Mister Bean's car, the lime green 1977 Mini with the padlock on the door. Ruby doesn't participate much in family discussions. Morty would say during dinner loud enough for me to hear, I don't have much to add about stock portfolios. I'd reply, but I can explain why Mister Bean's mini needs custom suspension if anyone's interested. Silence was always beautiful. While my cousins performed interest they didn't have, I openly admitted I found his world boring and would rather talk about a comedy car. They spent weekends at his house pretending to enjoy golf. I worked double shifts and saved for community college while they argued about investment strategies. I Learned welding to fabricate custom parts. Why waste time on a joke car? Madison would ask, it's not a joke just because it makes people smile. I'd tell her. Morty would try to draw me in. Ruby, what do you think about the market? No idea. I'd answer honestly. But I figured out how to retro fit the original steering system, which is genuinely exciting. He couldn't figure out my angle because I didn't have one. I genuinely found his world uninteresting and was building my own path without his validation. The more my cousins competed, the more dismissive he became of them. The more I focused on my car, the more curious he got. Why Mister Bean's car? He asked once. Because it's iconic, mechanically interesting, and makes people happy. That feel.

Three years ago, she called me crying. She was about to be evicted and had nowhere to go. She asked if I could help just this once. I said yes. Her rent was 2,500 a month. She seems happy. Each update felt like another knife. But slowly I started healing, made actual friends through a book club, got promoted twice, started running again. Therapy helped me understand that their betrayal said everything about them and nothing about my worth. I stopped checking my sister's Instagram, stopped defining my life by what I'd lost. His voice is calm, but there's something cold underneath. I look up for my laptop, confused. Where's what? My watch, he says. The Rolex. It was in my drawer yesterday and now it's gone. My mom stops what she's doing. Rachel puts down her phone. They both look at me. My stomach drops because I can already see where this is going. I haven't touched your watch, I say. I didn't even know it was missing. My mom crosses her arms. You've been in his office a lot lately, late at night. What were you doing in there? Printing scholarship applications. I tell her the printer in my room is broken. I've been using dad's. Rachel laughs. Sure you were. I saw you going through his desk drawers last week. You were definitely looking for something. I wasn't going through anything, I say, my voice rising. I was Looking for printer paper. She shrugs like she doesn't believe me. My dad's face hardens. This isn't a joke, Liam. That watch is worth more than your car. If you took it, you need to tell me now I didn't take it. I repeat, I swear I didn't touch it. My mom shakes her head. You've always been secretive, always hiding things. Now this, Rachel, adds fuel to the fire. He's probably trying to sell it for cash. You know, he's been talking about starting some business thing. My dad stares at me for a long moment. Then he says the words that change everything, pack your things. You're not staying here anymore. I think he's bluffing at first, but he's not. He stands there, arms crossed, waiting. My mom doesn't say anything to stop him. Rachel actually smirks when I try to defend myself again. My dad just points toward the stairs. I pack one duffle bag, clothes, laptop, charger. I can hear them downstairs talking in low voices, probably deciding I'm guilty. When I come back down, my dad hands me $100 and says, that's all I'm getting. It's Christmas Eve. Snow's coming down hard. I sit in my car in a grocery store parking lot for two hours trying to figure out where to go. Eventually, I drive to my friend's house and sleep on his couch. The next few months are a blur. I bounce between couches, sleep in my car. When I run out of Options pick up shifts at auto shop during the day and deliver food at night. I'm working 70 hour weeks just to stay off the street. My Aunt Beatrice finally tracks me down through a mutual friend. She gives me her spare room and gets me a steady job at her friend's garage. No questions asked, no judgment, just help. I don't talk to my parents. They don't reach out. Rachel posts pictures on social media of family dinners I'm not invited to. My mom captions them, grateful for the family we have like I never existed. Two years pass. I save everything I make. I start a small car flipping business on the side. Nothing fancy, just buying broken down cars, fixing them.

voice_to_text: I found my boss's performance review for me in the printer, lazy, entitled, always on his phone. I said nothing, just started documenting everything. Six months later, he called me into his office with HR. I've been working as a junior analyst at Michelin Cross for 3 years. The pay was decent, work was straightforward, and I actually enjoyed what I did. But my boss, Derek, had this way of making me feel like I was constantly failing, even when I wasn't. He'd walk past my desk without acknowledging me for days. Then suddenly when a client complained or a report was late, I'd be pulled into his office for a lecture about accountability and professionalism. It didn't matter if the mistake was actually his or someone else's. I was the easiest target. One Tuesday afternoon, I walked to the shared printer on our floor to grab some contract copies I'd sent over. The machine was still warm, spitting out pages. And there, face up on the tray was a document with my name at the top, employee performance Review confidential. I glanced around. The floor was quiet. Most people were at lunch. I picked it up and started reading. Derek's notes. Shows up late, constantly spends half the day on personal calls and texting, barely meets minimum standards, does not take initiative, recommend no raise this cycle, possible Pip if behavior continues. My stomach dropped. I read it again, slower this time, thinking maybe I misunderstood. But no, it Was right there, black ink on white paper. The thing is, none of it was true. Been arriving at least 15 minutes early every single day for the past year. I made coffee, prepped reports, answered early emails before anyone else even got in. My phone usage was almost entirely work related. Tracking project updates in our client portal app or coordinating with the sales team performance. I'd closed more accounts in the last quarter than anyone else on the team. Three major clients had specifically requested to work with me again. I stood there holding that paper, hand shaking, not from sadness but from pure anger. I took a photo with my phone. Then I put the document back exactly where I found it and walk back to my desk. That's when I decided no confrontation, no emotional outburst. It's cold, detailed evidence. I started keeping receipts on everything. Every email I sent I BCC to my personal account with time stamps. Every client win I documented with confirmations and thank you notes. Every morning I arrived early, I sent myself a photo of the office clock showing the time. I tracked Derek's schedule too. The two hour lunches while I covered his client calls. The days he left at 3 for meetings that didn't exist. I saved the Slack message where he told me to lie to a client about why a deliverable was late, a deadline he'd missed, not me. I kept a spreadsheet, dates, times, evidence Six months of my actual work compared to his false narrative. My folder grew thick with proof. Then one morning in March, Derek's assistant messaged me, Derek needs to see you in Conference Room B at two PM HR will be there. My heart rate spiked, but I stayed calm. I knew what this was. At two PM, I walked in. Derek sat on one side of the table, arms crossed, looking annoyed.

College tuition paid in full without her lifting a finger. Me, I got a bus pass and a lecture about building character. When I asked for help with community college costs, dad said I'd appreciate my education more if I earned it myself. So I did. I worked weekends at a grocery store, picked up night shifts at a warehouse, took out loans I'm still paying off. Every dollar I made went toward tuition or rent or keeping myself fed. Meanwhile, Lily posted Instagram photos from spring break trips I could never afford. But I kept grinding. Got my engineering degree, landed a solid job, and started saving obsessively. No fancy dinners, no vacations, no new clothes, unless the old ones had holes. For five straight years, I funneled every bonus, every overtime check, every tax refund into one account. My house fund. When I finally had enough for a down payment, I found a small two bedroom condo on the edge of town. Nothing fancy, but it was mine. I called mom crying when my offer got accepted. She actually seemed happy for me. Threw me a little Celebration. Dinner that weekend. Lily showed up late, sat in the corner stirring her wine glass. Must be nice having that engineering salary, she muttered. Some of us are still paying off grad school. I tried to ignore the sting. Mom changed the subject quickly. The day I closed on the condo, dad came by to see it. Walked through every room, nodded slowly. Smart investment if you did it right, he said. I thought that was his version of being proud. Two weeks later, a process server knocked on my door. Legal paper. My parents were suing me for the house. I called dad immediately, hands shaking. What is this? His voice was cold. Matter of fact, that house belongs to your sister. Your mother and I discussed this with our attorney. The down payment came from inheritance money that was meant for Lily's first home. I felt like I've been punched. What inheritance? Grandma split everything equally. I never touched that money. Every cent for this house came from my paychecks. You're making this more complicated than it needs to be, he said. Lily needs that house more than you do. She's planning for it. You can buy another one later. I hung up and immediately called my bank. Pulled every statement from the last five years. Every deposit had a clear paper trail. Payroll transfers, direct deposits. Nothing from any inheritance account. When we got to court, their lawyer painted this picture of a greedy daughter who'd stolen Her sister's dream. Dad took the stand first. Confident and calm. He testified about a long standing family understanding that grandma's inheritance money was earmarked for Lily's first home purchase. Mom went next, dabbing her eyes with a you. Talked about how much Lily had sacrificed. How she didn't make as much money as me. How unfair it was that I'd used family money to get ahead. She made it sound like I'd robbed them. Lily sat at their table looking wounded, like I betrayed her somehow. A few relatives in the gallery nodded along sympathetically. Then my lawyer stood up. She sent a thick folder to the judge. voice_to_text: I found my boss's performance review for me in the printer, lazy, entitled, always on his phone. I said nothing, just started documenting everything. Six months later, he called me into his office with HR. I've been working as a junior analyst at Michelin Cross for 3 years. The pay was decent, work was straightforward, and I actually enjoyed what I did. But my boss, Derek, had this way of making me feel like I was constantly failing, even when I wasn't. He'd walk past my desk without acknowledging me for days. Then suddenly when a client complained or a report was late, I'd be pulled into his office for a lecture about accountability and professionalism. It didn't matter if the mistake was actually his or someone else's. I was the easiest target. One Tuesday afternoon, I walked to the shared printer on our floor to grab some contract copies I'd sent over. The machine was still warm, spitting out pages. And there, face up on the tray was a document with my name at the top, employee performance review confidential. So I glanced around. The floor was quiet. Most people were at lunch. I picked it up and started reading. Derek's notes. Shows up late, constantly spends half the day on personal calls and texting, barely meets minimum standards, does not take initiative, recommend no raise this cycle, possible Pip if behavior continues. My stomach dropped. Read it again, slower this time, thinking maybe I'd misunderstood. But no, it Was right there, black ink on white paper. The thing is, none of it was true. I've been arriving at least 15 minutes early every single day for the past year. I made coffee, prepped reports, answered early emails before anyone else even got in. My phone usage was almost entirely work related, tracking project updates in our client portal app or coordinating with the sales team and performance. I'd closed more accounts in the last quarter than anyone else on the team. Three major clients had specifically requested to work with me again. I stood there holding that paper, hand shaking, not from sadness but from pure anger. I took a photo with my phone, then I put the document back exactly where I found it and walk back to my desk. That's when I decided no confrontation, no emotional outburst, cold detailed evidence. I started keeping receipts on everything. Every email I sent I BCC to my personal account with time stamps. Every client win I documented with confirmations and thank you notes. Every morning I arrived early, I sent myself a photo of the office clock showing the time. I tracked Derek's schedule too. The two hour lunches while I covered his client calls. The days he left at 3 for meetings that didn't exist. I saved the Slack message where he told me to lie to a client about why a deliverable was late, a deadline he'd missed, not me. I kept a spreadsheet, dates, times Evidence, six months of my actual work compared to his false narrative. My folder grew thick with proof. Then one morning in March, Derek's assistant messaged me, Derek needs to see you in Conference Room B at two PM HR will be there. My heart rate spiked, but I stayed calm. I knew what this was. At two PM, I walked in. Derek sat on one side of the.

This time, she gives everything she has. She studies the woman's movements, her expressions, her rhythm. Still, something feels off. While she practices the dance, the woman's ghost appears right behind her. The movie is called The Spiritualists.

voice_to_text: The man hurried into the restroom, not expecting to find a housekeeper cleaning inside. Lisa quickly apologized and stepped out in a rush. Even after leaving, her heart was still racing. The man's handsome face and confident posture had completely caught her off guard. But when she turned and saw the cleaning tools in her hands, she forced herself to calm down. Anyone staying in a hotel like this had to be wealthy or influential. And she was just a single mom earning a modest wage. Someone who didn't even dare to dream about love, let alone mingling with powerful people. What Lisa never expected was that this powerful man would seek her out the very next day. Because she had no one to watch her son during his weekend break, Lisa had to bring him to the hotel and leave him with a coworker. As John rode the elevator alone to the restroom, he came across a familiar face. I know who you are. Yeah? What do you know? I know that you're the state senator. I know that you're thinking of running for senator. I know your voting record and your consistent stand on environmental causes. The man was the same guest Lisa had run into while cleaning the day before. Jack wasn't just a strong candidate for the Senate. He was wealthy, always surrounded by bodyguards, and luxury cars were practically standard for him. Yet a man that important found himself impressed by a ten year old Boy standing in front of him. There was a maturity in John that no child his age should have. He even had sharp insights about the current political climate that genuinely surprised Jack. Intrigued, Jack invited him to take a walk at the park. But John turned him down. He had promised his mom he wouldn't leave her side. Meanwhile, inside the suite, Lisa and her coworker were admiring a guest's coat. The price tag alone made them sigh. One year of their salary wouldn't even cover it. Her coworker picked up a dress and insisted Lisa try it on. Lisa wanted to refuse, but eventually gave in after enough persuasion. And just as she was changing, John showed up with Jack. Jack didn't realize that the woman in the dress was the same housekeeper he'd seen the previous day. He approached her with a warm smile and introduced himself politely. Seeing an opportunity, the coworker jumped in to help. You want your coat? What? Why? That could be so tricky. Here. Why aren't you just saying what a beautiful day it was? Are you going out? Weren't you saying how you wanted to stretch your legs? Well, if your husband wouldn't mind. Lisa suddenly found herself mistaken for a guest rather than staff. She wanted to take off the coat and clarify everything, but Jack's invitation cut her off. His charming smile made her heart flutter in spite of herself. Before she knew it, she agreed. But as they Reached the elevator, Lisa spotted the hotel manager. Panicking, she turned around and pretended to adjust her son's clothes. She kept her back to the manager as she slipped into the elevator, carefully avoiding eye contact. Her heart didn't settle until they finally made it out of the hotel. What she didn't expect was the crowd of reporters waiting outside to interview Jack. While she was questioning her son about what had happened, Jack finished speaking with the reporters and hurried toward them. Watching the small boy walk away, Jack couldn't help but feel curious. How could someone so young know so much about politics? It turned out John had always been shy as a child. He had trouble making friends at school and froze whenever he stood at a podium. But while one door closed for him, another opened. He had an incredible memory for anything he saw on TV. He absorbed news instant and developed strong judgment about the world around him. The two of them eventually reached a bench. To avoid getting the expensive coat dirty, Lisa pulled John back just in time. Oh, Lord! I almost sat on your face right there! Tiny moment broke the ice between them, and the atmosphere instantly felt much more relaxed.

voice_to_text: After finishing my meal at my sister's restaurant, I was about to leave when the manager called out, sir, you haven't paid your Bill yet. I looked at the unfamiliar face, thinking he must be new and didn't recognize me, so I politely explained. Just put it on your boss's tab. She knows about it. The mail manager gave me a dismissive glance. Sir, this is a three Michelin star restaurant. We never allow tabs. He finished speaking, then handed me a printed Bill. I glanced down at it. A single meal, half a million dollars. Glow up cutlery maintenance fee $30,000 exclusive air purification fee $50,000 VIP emotional appeasement service fee $100,000 and a bunch of other ridiculous charges. I had no idea my sister ran such a rip off joint. I let out a sarcastic laugh. I'm Adrian Hayes, Miss Hayes's brother. If there's an issue, she can come home and talk to me. But he wouldn't back down. If you can't afford it, just say so. Don't try to piggyback on Miss Hayes's name. I've seen plenty of pretty boys trying to sponge off women. I texted my assistant. Astros, tell my sister, either fire this guy or I'm pulling all my investments. Sir, stop wasting everyone's time. Just pay. His tone was smug and cutting, as if he'd already labeled me a scoundrel trying to climb the ladder on a woman's coat tails. Several curious glances were already turning my way. I frowned, not wanting to Waste time on such a ridiculous matter? I pulled out my phone and dialed my sister's number directly, but all I got was a cold, busy signal. I tried again. Same result. It's a weekday. What's that girl up to? I put down my phone and looked straight at the aggressive man, repeating each word clearly. I'll say it again. My name is Adrian Hayes, and I am the biological brother of your boss, Serena Hayes. Her phone isn't answering right now. You can check her card. My photo and information are linked to it. I thought this was the most direct and effective way to solve the problem. But when the male manager heard my name, instead of verifying it, he burst into a loud, exaggerated and grating laugh. He laughed so hard he almost doubled over, drawing even more attention. Then he suddenly leaned in close, lowering his voice to a whisper only we could hear. Still pretending. I've seen your face in Serena's photo album a thousand times. You're that persistent creep who always tries to interfere with our lives. And now you have the nerve to show up at her restaurant and put your tab on her. Who do you think you are? I froze for a second, then glanced at his name tag. Brendan Miller. An overwhelming sense of exasperation washed over me. Serena's boyfriend. The one she'd been so secretive about. The one she wouldn't even let me see a single photo of it. Turned out to be this foolish, venomous man right in front of me. How could her taste be this bad? It dawned on me then. Today's half million dollar exorbitant Bill wasn't a misunderstanding at all. It was a premeditated humiliation. Before I could even speak, he completely lost his patience. If this gentleman insists on dining and dashing, we'll have to restrain him until the police arrive. He waved his hand and two burly security guards who had been standing nearby immediately stepped forward. They were two well trained, strong men, two fists against four hands. My resistance was quickly subdued and my arms were twisted tightly behind my back. I struggled violently, but couldn't break free from their professional hold. They ignored my furious gaze and the frightened looks of the other guests, roughly dragging me towards the back kitchen. Then I was violently shoved into the storeroom in the back, reeking of disinfectant and stale, greasy slop. The door slammed shut, cutting off all light and sound from outside in the dark. The male manager said nothing. He simply raised his leather clad foot and kicked me hard in the stomach. The excruciating pain made me grunt instantly, my stomach churning. That's for spending my woman's money! That's for meddling in her business! He yelled, his voice twisted by jealousy and rage. He looked down at me, then ordered the two burly men beat him! Teach him a lesson! The two security guards were clearly his cronies. They didn't hesitate, a relentless flurry of punches and kicks raining down on me. I gritted my teeth, swallowing every cry of pain. My bones felt like they were being crushed. Inch by inch, my internal organs dislodged. His taunts continued. Who do you think you are, huh? Just a good for nothing leeching off his sister? I told you, I'm her brother. If you don't believe me, ask Serena. Call her now. I'll talk to her. I struggled to explain, but the man in front of me just ignored it. It wasn't until I started feeling dizzy that he raised a hand, signaling them to stop. He nudged my shoulder with the tip of his leather shoe, looking at me triumphantly. You better settle the Bill today and cough up another half million. That's the consequence of you interfering in my relationship with Serena and spending her money. I'm not afraid of trouble. Serena will handle any fallout for me. I was curled in a ball of pain, weakly trying to argue. That's my own money, I told you. If you don't believe me, go ask her. His face changed. He kicked me, and the two security guards immediately understood, their punches and kicks raining down on me again. I knew he wouldn't listen to anything I said. If this continued, I could be seriously hurt. After I coughed up a mouthful of blood, I used my last ounce of strength to grope for my phone on the floor. Stop! I'll pay. He seemed satisfied with my submission, signaling the two security guards to stop, squatted down and patted my swollen cheek. See? Wouldn't it have been easier to just do that from the start? You chose the hard way. Two million, not a cent less. I lay sprawled on the cold floor, gasping for breath, my lungs burning. I ignored him and dialed my friend Leo Rodriguez's number. The phone was answered quickly. Leo, bring two million to my sister's restaurant. I need it now. Leo, on the other end, paused, then said something was wrong. Adrian, what's wrong, man? Your voice sounds. Don't ask, just hurry. I cut him off and hung up. Brendan's eyes instantly lit up at the mention of two million. A greedy glint flashed in them. He probably thought I was beaten into submission, offering more money to beg for mercy. The triumph on his face was now impossible to hide. Smart move. Leo's speed was astonishing. Soon the storeroom door was violently shoved open from the outside. Leo, accompanied by two bodyguards, strode in quickly. He was shocked to see the blood on my mouth, my disheveled clothes, and my pathetic posture propped up on the floor. He rushed over to help me up. I shook my head, subtly signalling him to stay silent, then took the bank card he handed me with the PIN attached and tossed it to the man. The man took the card and didn't bother me further. Waving his hand, if that's a fake card, I have countless ways to find you. Get lost! Enduring the excruciating pain throughout my body, I limped out of that sickening place, leaning on Leo's arm. When we reached the entrance, I thanked Leo. Thanks, Buddy. I'll get this sorted and pay you back quickly. He looked at me worriedly. Don't worry about the money. It's nothing. But what happened to you, I sneered. My sister found herself a fine boyfriend. I guess I have a score to settle with her. I pulled out my phone and found the number for the restaurant's assistant general manager, Mr. Peterson. Mr. Peterson was the restaurant's actual manager, someone I had personally recruited, and he was quite loyal to me. The call connected. I wasted no words, my voice devoid of emotion. You have 10 minutes to fire a manager named Brendan Miller. Otherwise Hayes Enterprises will withdraw all investment from the restaurant. Every last cent. Mr. Peterson, on the other end, was scared shitless the moment he heard my voice. He must have heard the weakness and the unusual edge in my voice as he agreed in quick, terrified succession. Not even daring to ask why, I hung up the phone and without a moment's pause, told Leo to take me straight to the police station. With the clearest, calmest logic, I recounted everything that had just happened to the officer who assisted me. After giving a detailed statement at the police station, I went to the hospital for an injury assessment. I held that thin report in my hand, and the fury of betrayal, as if fueled by hot oil, burned hotter and fiercer within me. I needed an explanation. I needed Serena Hayes to give me an explanation herself. My assistant found out Serena was at her villa. My driver and bodyguards arrived, and we headed straight for Serena's place. That villa was also a gift for me. However, when I arrived, I was greeted by blaring heavy metal music and the raucous sounds of men and women echoing through the doors and windows. She was throwing a party. No wonder she hadn't answered my calls. The villa's main door was ajar, and on a strange impulse, I didn't push it open immediately. Soon I heard a familiar male voice. It was Brendan Miller. He was pouring out his story to everyone, painting himself as a poor, helpless victim bullied by an arrogant third party, EMI, who then had the audacity to turn the tables and accuse him. I just asked him to pay the Bill, and he threw $2 million in my face, then found people to get me fired. Serena, he's gone too far. He doesn't respect you at all. He just wants to humiliate me. He just wants us to break up. Inside, Serena's circle of friends, mostly hangers on and troublemakers, echoed his outrage. Serena, in turn, was loudly comforting Brendan in her arms, her voice full of Tenderness and indulgence. Brendan, don't worry, I won't let you suffer this injustice. Then, as if to prove her resolve, she promised everyone confidently, when I get my hands on my brother, I'll make him beg for your forgiveness on his knees. Inside, those spoiled brats were still backing Brendan, shouting about how they would make me pay. Serena, just say the word and we'll go drag that bastard out right now! Yeah, let him know who truly owns this place! I couldn't listen anymore. I raised a hand and my bodyguard kicked open the villa's front door. The booming music screeched to a halt, the noisy laughter instantly vanishing. Dozens of stunned eyes all at once turn towards the doorway. No need to drag me out, I'm right here. Who wants to teach me a lesson? How to read part 2? Type the lower left corner of the video. Download it. Search my code to follow.

voice_to_text: My parents filed a lawsuit over my house. When I asked, my dad said, it belongs to your sister. But I showed them every deposit and one in court. Growing up, I Learned early that fairness wasn't something our family believed in. My sister Lily got everything. Ballet lessons that cost hundreds a month, a brand new Honda at 16. College tuition paid in full without her lifting a finger. Me, I got a bus pass and a lecture about building character. When I asked for help with community college costs, dad said I'd appreciate my education more if I earned it myself. So I did. I worked weekends at a grocery store, picked up night shifts at a warehouse, took out loans I'm still paying off. Every dollar I made went toward tuition or rent or keeping myself fed. Meanwhile, Lily posted Instagram photos from spring break trips I could never afford. But I kept grinding. Got my engineering degree, landed a solid job, and started saving obsessively. No fancy dinners, no vacations, no new clothes, unless the old ones had holes. For five straight years, I funneled every bonus, every overtime check, every tax refund into one account. My house fund. When I finally had enough for a down payment, I found a small two bedroom condo on the edge of town. Nothing fancy, but it was mine. I called mom crying when my offer got accepted. She actually seemed happy for me. Threw me a little Celebration. Dinner that weekend. Lily showed up late, sat in the corner stirring her wine glass. Must be nice having that engineering salary, she muttered. Some of us are still paying off grad school. I tried to ignore the sting. Mom changed the subject quickly. The day I closed on the condo, dad came by to see it. Walked through every room, nodded slowly. Smart investment if you did it right, he said. I thought that was his version of being proud. Two weeks later, a process server knocked on my door. Legal paper. My parents were suing me for the house. I called dad immediately, hands shaking. What is this? His voice was cold. Matter of fact, that house belongs to your sister. Your mother and I discussed this with our attorney. The down payment came from inheritance money that was meant for Lily's first home. I felt like I've been punched. What inheritance? Grandma split everything equally. I never touched that money. Every cent for this house came from my paychecks. You're making this more complicated than it needs to be, he said. Lily needs that house more than you do. She's planning for it. You can buy another one later. I hung up and immediately called my bank. Pulled every statement from the last five years. Every deposit had a clear paper trail. Payroll transfers, direct deposits. Nothing from any inheritance account. When we got to court, their lawyer painted this picture of a greedy daughter who'd stolen Her sister's dream. Dad took the stand first. Confident and calm. He testified about a long standing family understanding that grandma's inheritance money was earmarked for Lily's first home purchase. Mom went next, dabbing her eyes with a tissue. Talked about how much Lily had sacrificed, how she didn't make as much money as me, how unfair it was that I'd used family money to get ahead. She made it sound like I'd robbed them. Lily sat at their table looking wounded, like betrayed her somehow. A few relatives in the gallery nodded along sympathetically. Then my lawyer stood up. She presented a thick folder to the judge. Five years of pay stubs. Every single one. Transfer records showing money moving from my employer directly to my personal savings account. Bank statements with highlighted deposits, each one labeled and dated tax returns.

And tonight she'd crash with my 15 year old in the car. The coach in his phone was her. She'd saved herself that way so I'd never suspect if I saw the name. I found one more thing, a hospital bracelet in his jacket from two months ago. She'd taken him to a different hospital, paid cash, never told me the discharge papers were in his backpack. Patient advised to avoid high speed activity. She knew, she knew he'd been hurt before and kept racing with him anyway. Doctor Rodriguez returned Mr Park. The decision. I looked at my mother. Her heart valve issue was real but manageable. She could wait hours for surgery. She'd exaggerated the urgency knowing I'd choose her over my son, counting on guilt.
